The US "Christian Genocide" Narrative:
In November 2025, President Trump declared Nigeria a "Country of Particular Concern" and threatened direct military action against Islamist militant groups, claiming 7,000 Nigerian Christians had been killed in 2025 alone Modern Ghana. However, data shows that while attacks on churches have increased in recent years, both churches and mosques have been targeted, with more mosque attacks in 2015 and 2017 Modern Ghana.
According to data from the Armed Conflict Location and Event Data program, between January 2020 and September 2025, there were 385 attacks resulting in 317 deaths against Christians where religious identity played a factor, compared to 417 Muslim deaths in 196 attacks ScienceDirect. The reality appears far more complex than a simple "Christian genocide."
Who Already Controls the Resources:
This is where it gets really interesting. More than 80 percent of mining projects in Nigeria's lithium sector are financed by Chinese investors, who also own the majority of processing and mining companies Persecution.org. Since September 2023, Chinese companies such as Canmax Technology, Jiuling Lithium, Avatar New Energy Nigeria Company, and Asba have invested more than $1.3 billion in lithium processing Persecution.org.
Companies such as Avatar and Ganfeng Limited are building lithium processing facilities in Nasarawa State, while Jupiter Lithium Limited and ReElement Technologies have announced a joint venture targeting deposits in Kaduna State Persecution.org.
There is one notable US company: Continental Lithium, a Nigerian-American company founded in 2017, describes itself as among the largest landholders of lithium assets in Africa with approximately 152,000 acres across 26 licenses Barnabas Aid.
